04753nam a22006135i 9780292767690DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211978txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927676907 a10.7560/7033152doi  a(DE-B1597)587517  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aHX851 7aPOL0420102bisacsh04a335.831 aHart, John M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAnarchism & The Mexican Working Class, 1860-1931 /cJohn M. Hart. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1978  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tANARCHISM & THE MEXICAN WORKING CLASH, 1860-1931 -- t1. The Origins of Mexican Anarchism -- t2. The Proselytizer -- t3. The Organizers -- t4. The Anarchists and the Origins of the Urban Labor Movement -- t5. Nineteenth-Century Anarchism and the Agrarian Movement -- t6. Decline and Perseverance -- t7. The Resurgence -- t8. Anarchism, the Working Class, and the Opening Phases of the Revolution -- t9. The Casa del Obrero Mundial and the Constitutionalists -- t10. The Aftermath of August 1916: Continued Activity -- t11. Conclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliographic Note -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe anarchist movement had a crucial impact upon the Mexican working class between 1860 and 1931. John M. Hart destroys some old myths and brings new information to light as he explores anarchism's effect on the development of the Mexican urban working-class and agrarian movements. Hart shows how the ideas of European anarchist thinkers took root in Mexico, how they influenced revolutionary tendencies there, and why anarchism was ultimately unsuccessful in producing real social change in Mexico. He explains the role of the working classes during the Mexican Revolution, the conflict between urban revolutionary groups and peasants, and the ensuing confrontation between the new revolutionary elite and the urban working class. The anarchist tradition traced in this study is extremely complex. It involves various social classes, including intellectuals, artisans, and ordinary workers; changing social conditions; and political and revolutionary events which reshaped ideologies. During the nineteenth century the anarchists could be distinguished from their various working- class socialist and trade unionist counterparts by their singular opposition to government. In the twentieth century the lines became even clearer because of hardening anarchosyndicalist, anarchistcommunist, trade unionist, and Marxist doctrines. In charting the rise and fall of anarchism, Hart gives full credit to the roles of other forms of socialism and Marxism in Mexican working-class history. Mexican anarchists whose contributions are examined here include nineteenth-century leaders Plotino Rhodakanaty, Santiago Villanueva, Francisco Zalacosta, and José María Gonzales; the twentieth-century revolutionary precursor Ricardo Flores Magón; the Casa del Obrero founders Amadeo Ferrés, Juan Francisco Moncaleano, and Rafael Quintero; and the majority of the Centro Sindicalista Ubertario, leaders of the General Confederation of Workers. This work is based largely on primary sources, and the bibliography contains a definitive listing of anarchist and radical working-class newspapers for the period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aAnarchismzMexicoxHistory. 0aWorking classzMexicoxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Anarchism.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292767690423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292767690/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL